00:38:57.400 --> 00:39:00.460
you wore your matching
outfits today.

00:39:00.460 --> 00:39:03.050
ALAN INY: Yesterday, too,
by coincidence.

00:39:03.050 --> 00:39:06.612
AUDIENCE: You've spent a lot
of time together, I assume.

00:39:06.612 --> 00:39:07.770
LUC DE BRABANDERE: So probably
the first thing to do is to

00:39:07.770 --> 00:39:11.212
give a good definition
of what is to doubt.

00:39:11.212 --> 00:39:16.070
To doubt is not a kind
of bad feeling.

00:39:16.070 --> 00:39:22.190
It's about, remember, at any
time that here, you only have

00:39:22.190 --> 00:39:24.110
simplifications.

00:39:24.110 --> 00:39:27.920
So that's to doubt.

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:31.460
I like to tell, great
managers never

00:39:31.460 --> 00:39:34.600
hesitate and always doubt.

00:39:34.600 --> 00:39:37.830
So if you're a manager, and
somebody asks you, the client

00:39:37.830 --> 00:39:39.360
doesn't pay-- send a reminder.

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:40.780
The machine is broken--

00:39:40.780 --> 00:39:41.590
call the company.

00:39:41.590 --> 00:39:43.510
You don't hesitate.

00:39:43.510 --> 00:39:47.740
But you should remember at any
time that if it's possible for

00:39:47.740 --> 00:39:53.270
you not to hesitate, it is
because one day you select one

00:39:53.270 --> 00:39:56.730
simplification, a strategy,
you're going to do this.

00:39:56.730 --> 00:39:58.910
And doubt is on the
other side.

00:39:58.910 --> 00:40:00.960
It's just a reminder.

00:40:00.960 --> 00:40:07.532
It's just, we are built with
simplification in our mind,

00:40:07.532 --> 00:40:08.030
assumption.

00:40:08.030 --> 00:40:11.430
And to doubt is from time to
time to challenge those

00:40:11.430 --> 00:40:12.710
assumptions.

00:40:12.710 --> 00:40:17.320
So to answer your question, the
first thing to I believe,

00:40:17.320 --> 00:40:21.080
is to list your assumptions.

00:40:21.080 --> 00:40:24.010
And sometimes they
are unconscious.

00:40:24.010 --> 00:40:26.780
We always said this,
why [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:26.780 --> 00:40:29.960
Maybe we can do that
differently.

00:40:29.960 --> 00:40:32.880
So you know what I mean?

00:40:32.880 --> 00:40:33.880
ALAN INY: Let me add
to that and give a

00:40:33.880 --> 00:40:35.420
business example as well.

00:40:35.420 --> 00:40:38.390
Because I think this idea of,
identifying as many of your

00:40:38.390 --> 00:40:39.110
assumptions--

00:40:39.110 --> 00:40:41.210
and of course you can't change
them all at the same time.

00:40:41.210 --> 00:40:44.060
That's when you would
become sort of a

00:40:44.060 --> 00:40:46.070
caricature of a good manager.

00:40:46.070 --> 00:40:47.440
You can't change everything.

00:40:47.440 --> 00:40:51.770
But imagine 40, 50 years ago,
all of the airlines are the

00:40:51.770 --> 00:40:54.200
sort of traditional Pan Am,
British Airways type.

00:40:54.200 --> 00:40:57.060
And there's no such thing yet
as a low cost airline.

00:40:57.060 --> 00:41:00.010
So what are the very specific
assumptions and constraints

00:41:00.010 --> 00:41:00.740
that have to change?

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:04.150
Well, we have many types of
planes to serve different

00:41:04.150 --> 00:41:05.160
definitions.

00:41:05.160 --> 00:41:07.390
We have one type of plane,
because it's cheaper.

00:41:07.390 --> 00:41:09.730
We go to the main airports
in each city.

00:41:09.730 --> 00:41:12.170
We are going to go to
secondary airports.

00:41:12.170 --> 00:41:13.510
We have assigned seating.

00:41:13.510 --> 00:41:14.410
We have open seating.

00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:16.130
We have all-inclusive pricing.

00:41:16.130 --> 00:41:17.700
We have unbundled pricing.

00:41:17.700 --> 00:41:18.680
We use travel agents.

00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:19.510
We don't use travel agents.

00:41:19.510 --> 00:41:22.180
All of these things, to be very
specific about what your

00:41:22.180 --> 00:41:25.950
existing assumptions and boxes
are, and then figure out which

00:41:25.950 --> 00:41:28.750
ones of them you're very
deliberately going to change,

00:41:28.750 --> 00:41:30.620
which constraints you're
going to break--

00:41:30.620 --> 00:41:31.870
that's what we mean by doubt.

00:41:34.810 --> 00:41:37.000
What else?

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:40.645
AUDIENCE: One of the challenges
that comes to my

00:41:40.645 --> 00:41:43.318
mind is [INAUDIBLE] the velocity
of execution rate.

00:41:43.318 --> 00:41:47.886
We live in a world with this
[INAUDIBLE] pressure, we have

00:41:47.886 --> 00:41:49.170
to get things out.

00:41:49.170 --> 00:41:54.550
So this sounds great, but I'm
wondering if you have any tips

00:41:54.550 --> 00:41:57.620
on making it more practical,
sellable.

00:41:57.620 --> 00:42:00.868
Let's say you want to start
doubting, or like the person

00:42:00.868 --> 00:42:02.118
is [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:04.756 --> 00:42:08.130
You have to give yourself time
and space to allow for that

00:42:08.130 --> 00:42:09.610
exercise to happen.

00:42:09.610 --> 00:42:12.370
[INAUDIBLE].

00:42:12.370 --> 00:42:14.730
Have you faced that in
your discussions?

00:42:14.730 --> 00:42:20.390
And what has worked for you to
encourage and get people to

00:42:20.390 --> 00:42:24.030
actually say, aha, we need
to take this on.

00:42:24.030 --> 00:42:27.170
LUC DE BRABANDERE: Part of the
answer is called scenario.

00:42:27.170 --> 00:42:30.630
So part of the future
you can more or less

00:42:30.630 --> 00:42:33.540
expect, based on forecast.

00:42:33.540 --> 00:42:37.430
The other part [INAUDIBLE],
including the ash of volcano,

00:42:37.430 --> 00:42:40.320
there's no way to make
any kind of forecast.

00:42:40.320 --> 00:42:45.340
So we recommend to increase
preparation.

00:42:45.340 --> 00:42:48.630
And so if you take uncertainty
on the right side of my

00:42:48.630 --> 00:42:51.080
[INAUDIBLE], the other
side of the

00:42:51.080 --> 00:42:52.870
simplification is called scenario.

00:42:52.870 --> 00:42:55.490
In this particular case,
a set of scenarios.

00:42:55.490 --> 00:42:58.900
So there is a way to disseminate
the language of

00:42:58.900 --> 00:43:00.480
uncertainty.

00:43:00.480 --> 00:43:07.770
We did that, maybe fifty times
in company, just like this

00:43:07.770 --> 00:43:12.220
habit, to live with
uncertainty in

00:43:12.220 --> 00:43:14.120
your mind, like this.

00:43:14.120 --> 00:43:17.450
And so now you're thinking of
the best way to do that, using

00:43:17.450 --> 00:43:18.940
this method.

00:43:18.940 --> 00:43:23.660
ALAN INY: So I agree with the
idea of using scenarios to

00:43:23.660 --> 00:43:24.630
embrace uncertainty.

00:43:24.630 --> 00:43:27.250
Because even if our natural
tendency is to try and

00:43:27.250 --> 00:43:30.270
eliminate it, if we realize that
we never can, then let's

00:43:30.270 --> 00:43:31.140
embrace it.

00:43:31.140 --> 00:43:34.320
But on the more individual
level, in terms of how to

00:43:34.320 --> 00:43:38.910
foster doubt, how to set this
up in organizations, my best

00:43:38.910 --> 00:43:41.820
suggestion is that sometimes
these kinds of thought

00:43:41.820 --> 00:43:44.900
exercises, like describe your
company without using the most

00:43:44.900 --> 00:43:48.760
obvious words like coffee,
like Luc tried earlier--

00:43:48.760 --> 00:43:51.380
there's a lot of these that
can be done in 10 minutes.

00:43:51.380 --> 00:43:53.680
There's a lot of these that can
be done by shutting the

00:43:53.680 --> 00:43:56.650
laptop, taking a white piece of
paper, or a flip chart, or

00:43:56.650 --> 00:43:59.780
a blank document, whatever
you want.

00:43:59.780 --> 00:44:02.190
And just thinking
a little bit.

00:44:02.190 --> 00:44:05.330
You don't need to take eight
hours and methodically list

00:44:05.330 --> 00:44:06.900
all of your assumptions,
though over

00:44:06.900 --> 00:44:08.200
time that can't hurt.

00:44:08.200 --> 00:44:10.730
But to be very quick and
specific about it, you can

00:44:10.730 --> 00:44:11.980
still make some progress.

00:44:15.970 --> 00:44:17.220
What else?

00:44:20.170 --> 00:44:21.100
Please.

00:44:21.100 --> 00:44:24.690
AUDIENCE: Apart from the tip
jar example that you gave,

00:44:24.690 --> 00:44:28.830
what is one of the most
